04224nam a22006615i 9780674041929DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780674041929  a(DE-B1597)584882  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHQ662.5b.A25 1998 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a306.85/094952211 aPatterson, Cynthia B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Family in Greek History /cCynthia B. Patterson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Nineteenth-Century Paradigm of Greek Family History -- t2. The Family in Homer and Hesiod -- t3. Early Greek Law and the Family -- t4. Marriage and Adultery in Democratic Athens -- t5. Adultery Onstage and in Court -- t6. Public and Private in Early Hellenistic Athens -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe family, Cynthia Patterson demonstrates, played a key role in the political changes that mark the history of ancient Greece. From the archaic society portrayed in Homer and Hesiod to the Hellenistic age, the private world of the family and household was integral with and essential to the civic realm. Early Greek society was rooted not in clans but in individual households, and a man's or woman's place in the larger community was determined by relationships within those households. The development of the city-state did not result in loss of the family's power and authority, Patterson argues; rather, the protection of household relationships was an important element of early public law. The interaction of civic and family concerns in classical Athens is neatly articulated by the examples of marriage and adultery laws. In law courts and in theater performances, violation of marital relationships was presented as a public danger, the adulterer as a sexual thief. This is an understanding that fits the Athenian concept of the city as the highest form of family. The suppression of the cities with the ascendancy of Alexander's empire led to a new resolution of the relationship between public and private authority: the concept of a community of households, which is clearly exemplified in Menander's plays. Undercutting common interpretations of Greek experience as evolving from clan to patriarchal state, Patterson's insightful analysis sheds new light on the role of men and women in Greek culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDomestic relations in literature. 0aDomestic relationszGreecexHistory. 0aFamilies in literature. 0aFamilieszGreecexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067404192940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674041929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674041929/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK